reamers are equal. Cerulo and Ruane show how our social position ingrains itself on our mind’s eye, quietly influencing the nature of our dreams, whether we embrace dreaming or dream at all, and whether we believe that our dreams, from the attainable to the improbable, can become realities. They explore how inequalities stemming from social disadvantages pattern our dreams for ourselves, and how sociocultural disparities in how we dream exacerbate social inequalities and limit the life paths we believe are open to us.Drawing on a wealth of original interviews with people from diverse social backgrounds, Dreams of a Lifetime demonstrates how the study of our dreams can provide new avenues for understanding and combatting inequality—including inequalities that precede action or outcome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAmbition. 0aDesire. 0aDreams. 0aFantasy. 0aIdentity (Psychology) 0aIdentity (Psychology). 0aSelf-actualization (Psychology) 0aSelf-actualization (Psychology). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAbdomen.  aAddition.  aAmericans.  aAmphisbaenia.  aAnatomy of Hope.  aAnd babies.  aAnn Swidler.  aAppendage.  aAsexual reproduction.  aBudding.  aCareer.  aCertification.  aCess.  aCestoda.  aCoccyx.  aComrade.  aConcept.  aConsciousness.  aCopayment.  aCultural capital.  aCulture.  aDesigner.  aDream Story.  aDuke University Press.  aEmployment.  aEntrepreneurship.  aEvolution.  aEvolutionary developmental biology.  aExtracurricular activity.  aFamily.  aFinding.  aFixed income.  aFocus group.  aForelimb.  aGermline.  aGraduation Rate.  aGraduation.  aHistory.  aHymenoptera.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIllustration.  aImagination.  aIncome.  aIntention.  aInvention.  aLaborer.  aLamarckism.  aLif